# Components & Architecture (PWA)

## Folder Structure

| Folder | What goes here |
|---|---|
| `src/screens/[domain]/` | Route-level screen + scoped components/hooks/types |
| `src/components/` | Shared UI used by 2+ domains |
| `src/hooks/` | Global shared hooks (useOfflineStatus, etc.) |
| `src/utils/` | Pure functions, formatters, helpers — no React |
| `src/types/` | Global TypeScript types/interfaces |

## Component Rules

- **Shadcn first:** Check `src/components/ui/` before building custom elements.
- **Size limit:** Component > 100 lines → split into sub-components in the same folder.
- **Screen limit:** `screens/[domain]/index.tsx` must stay < 80 lines. Extract sections.
- **No logic in screens:** All data/async logic lives in `screens/[domain]/hooks/`.
- **Props:** Use `interface [Name]Props`. Always export it.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — small, typed, accessible
export interface StatusBadgeProps {
  status: 'pendente' | 'conferido' | 'avaria';
}

export const StatusBadge = ({ status }: StatusBadgeProps) => {
  const styles: Record<StatusBadgeProps['status'], string> = {
    pendente:  'bg-yellow-100 text-yellow-800',
    conferido: 'bg-green-100 text-green-800',
    avaria:    'bg-red-100 text-red-800',
  };

  return (
    <span className={`inline-flex items-center rounded-full px-2 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium ${styles[status]}`}>
      {status}
    </span>
  );
};
```

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — logic inside screen, no prop types, too long
export default function Screen() {
  const { data } = useQuery(...); // logic here
  return <div style={{ width: 312 }}>...</div>; // arbitrary value
}
```

## Naming Conventions

- Files: `PascalCase.tsx` for components, `camelCase.ts` for hooks/utils.
- Event handlers: prefix with `handle` → `handleSelect`, `handleSubmit`.
- Hooks: prefix with `use` → `useDemanda`, `useAvaria`.
- Named exports only — never `export default`.

## Async State UI (mandatory)

Every screen with async data must render three states:

```tsx
if (isLoading) return <[Domain]Skeleton />;
if (isError)   return <ErrorState message="..." />;
return <[Domain]List items={data} />;
```
